ixty interviews with officers, residents, and stakeholders in South LA’s “Lakeside” precinct, they show how police tactics amplified—rather than resolved—racial tensions, complicating partnership efforts, crime response and prevention, and accountability. Gascón and Roussell shine a new light on the residents of this neighborhood to address the enduring—and frequently explosive—conflicts between police and communities. At a time when these issues have taken center stage, this volume offers a critical understanding of how community policing really works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican AmericanszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aPolicexComplaints againstzCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aPolicezCaliforniazLos Angeles. 0aPolice-community relationszCaliforniazLos Angeles. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aBlack studies.  aLatino studies.  aadvocacy.  acivilian review boards.  acollaborative ethnography.  acollaborative governance.  acommunity governance.  acommunity policing.  aconsumer capitalism.  acorporate sponsorship.  acrime prevention.  agenealogy.  agovernmentality.  agrassroots activism.  alanguage differences.  alegality.  aliberalism.  amoral order.  aneighborhood disputes.  apathologization.  apolice accountability.  apolice authority.  apolice commission.  apolice legitimacy.  apolice workforce.  apoliceability.  apostindustrial city.  apost–civil rights era.  apublic complaints.  apublic perceptions.  apublic service.  arace relations.  aracial order.  aregulation.  arepression.  aresponsibilization.  ariot commission.  ariot commissions.  asocial change.  asocial organization.  astreet history.  asymbolic interaction.  aurban redevelopment.  aurban riots.